reviews.review_text: Nasty outside,Joyous inside! This was the 1st of 3 shows lifetime I didn't get in. It was cold and damp and the parking lot scene didn't help much. But what a show! Great songlist,excellent playing! Both sets start and finish strong. Vocals are very clear. The drum mix is superb! This show should put a smile on your face! Beautiful sdbd Peter and Bill! I'm Grateful to finally be able to hear what I missed. Thanks so much!
great setlist hard to believe they really didn't plan these out ahead of time.

I couldn't get past Must have been Roses Jerry sounds terrible. Everyone else trying to keep it together.  Who gave this 5 stars. that wrecks the rating system if everyone gives any dead show 5 stars because it's a 'dead show.'  Come on - they're all dead shows here.
Three I'll give it three plus. The next shows 11/7,8 were superb, especially for a 17 year old.

"Just look right besides you.." If you are a critic there is plenty of vocal flubs but then again I would rather listen to this tonight then the soundboard from this night in 1977.
Sometimes the grunge of 1985 is just the ticket.
 I believe this was one of the last fall tours that traveled the road less taken. They start doing those extended runs in fewer but much larger East Coast cities?
Being from N.Y.C it cracked me up that this town was not pronounced WAR_CHESTER but WOOOSTA especially when the spelling is Worchester.
But be that as it may. to me it was all these shows in the smaller cities of America that made the Dead so special. Stories of High School misfits going to the freak show and finding themselves to finally be home.
The Dead were somewhat similar to when the Carnies came to town with the fair. "Hang it up and see what tomorrow brings."
I tried mostly unsuccessfully to keep one foot on the concrete pavement and the other to barefoot boogie with the Grateful Dead.
I am listening as i write this. Dead played pretty jagged to start but as they hit Minglewood. I get the vibe that the sound is coming together. Sounds like some Sound board antics with slight Chula Vista forays. The slide is very nice and Brent is slashing.
Overall good sound quality. Like it is alive and bouncing. I like a soundboard that has enough crowd to get me fired up but none of the stupidity one often encountered dancing around and searching for the sound in the arena.
Big Railroad sounds just great. Seems like they are clicking now. This is another tune that seems to get forgotten but it is smokin' hot. I kinda like how everyone backs Garcia's lead vocals.
I had this pegged as a 3 but it has my interest enough now that I could be bumping it up.
Listen to Garcia play his guitar.
RxR Blues feels so JGB / Chuck Berry
Music, Yes indeed. A song that has no place being played in November but then again it is kinda like a Sunshine Daydream, November/ North East.
Good jam in the MNS.. they are well primed now!
Oh cool, A Might as Well just to rock just a tad harder before break. I really loved Dancing to this song. Another great thing about shows in 1985. Mighty Swell
Set Two- Express Train and absolutely why I toured.
The China>Rider>Playing is 5 star territory.
Terrapin a little slow getting going.
I am kinda surprised that over the years Terrapin seems to get some hard knocks.
 i always found it to be very movin' 
when it was played live.
What's the line from Believe it or Not
"In a world time forgot"
